<font color="#FF0000">CAMPEATER!</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 20 13:16:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Three young warriors decided to venture onto the plains to &quot;make Meat&quot; for their village. Their's was a poor village with few horses and many mouths to feed, situated near a life giving river.  Without strong horses, these young warriors were limited in range and time upon the plains.<br>
The plains... in those days... was not a place to cruise in your station wagon with a carload of kids... with water fountains here and there.. etc.<br>
Instead, these men were up against the tall Bluestem grass that grew above a man's head.  Lurking in ambush was Matho, the grizzly bear, Tatanka, the herd father, the buffalo bull, capable of goring puny men to their deaths.  The plains presented a serious challenge... but these young men went forth because of their love for their people.<br>
After a long day of no success, they noticed that Anpetuwi, the Father Sun was going to his sleeping robes in the West.  The dangers of a daytime prairie were nothing in comparison to being caught out there at night.  From the top of a small knoll they could see the tops of the cottonwoods, &quot;The Standing People,&quot; wood which points to the sky... and they knew the way home.  Trees, sparse on the prairie, usually followed the course of waterways.<br>
Like all good men faced with challenge they called upon their tired and thirsty bodies, their wit and wisdom... and certainly their strong spirits to began a slow trot that would traverse the long distance before nightfall.<br>
Enroute, a young warrior stopped and claimed that he had heard a strange sound.  His brothers anxious to get to the village waited restlessly a few moments, then urged him to move on in the failing light.<br>
After running several miles, the warrior stopped again and whispered that he had heard the sound more clearly... it was the sound of a crying child.  His brothers reminded him that they were on the high plains... no place for babies to be heard crying.  But he insisted on leaving the trail, venture into the dangerous tall grass and confirm his belief.  His companions, not inclined to abandon him urged him to hurry and vowed, with lances ready, that they would answer any call for help.  To their surprise, he emerged from the tall grass with a beautiful boy child in his arms... no longer crying but smiling and making the contented sounds of a baby.  The warriors ran faster to make up for lost time.  They ran faster, seeking those who knew the ways of being a mother.  Upon their reaching the village, the Chief... one who had no son, heard their incredible story and was filled with joy.  He asked his wife and oldest daughter to take this baby boy and raise him as his son.  He declared that a celebration take place.  By the light of a great fire there was feasting, singing and dancing until everyone was exhausted and returned to their lodges.  Even the camp dogs, satiated by the abundant scraps of food, soon fell into a deep sleep.  The camp grew dark.. except for the circle of red coals that glowed in the dark.. like a giant red eye staring into the darkness.. and the small fire that burned in the Chief's lodge.  The Chief's daughter, delighted by the turn of events, was making small boots for the new baby, when suddenly she heard men shouting..women and children crying...horses screaming and dogs snarling.  She woke her father who grabbed his weapons and dashed outside.<br>
He saw nothing in the darkness.. only the red glowing eye of coals.  In the distance he heard the mournful hoot of Hinhan, the night eagle, the portender of death...he ignored this message and returned to his sleeping robes, advising his daughter to relax and find sleep.  In her preparations to go to bed the young woman heard the sounds again.  She woke her mother... who began to cleanse the lodge of bad spirits and the sounds came again!  Grasping her daughter in fear, the old woman whispered, &quot;Those sounds come from the mouth of the boy-child... that is no baby.. that is Eyah the campeater disguised as something beautiful.  Quietly, they woke and informed the Chief.  He ordered a silent and immediate evacuation of the village.<br>
The people knew that Eyah had long weak legs and used stealth to devour his victims.  They chose to flee across the deepest part of the river with their elders and infants, with the three young warriors acting as a rear guard.<br>
In the Chief's lodge Eyah awoke.. the sweet smile faded from his beautiful face and he bellowed and roared as he transformed into a horrible monster with sharp horns, long teeth and fetid breath.  He grew larger than the tall teepee, casting it into the pit of coals.  In the burst of yellow light the people could see Eyah rising above the tree tops... there was not time to cross the river.<br>
The young warrior who had carried Eyah to the village turned to his two comrades and begged them to forget the vows of the White Horse Song.. he asked them to go with the people to protect them while he faced Eyah alone.  With pain in their hearts they obeyed his practical request.<br>
Eyah, staggering awkwardly... filled with rage.. saw the young warrior waiting in the middle of the trail and made a clumsey lunge for him.  The young warrior stepped deftly aside and ripped Eyah's stomach open with his sharp lance.  As the monster crashed to the ground a host of shouting warriors, crying women and children, screaming horses and snarling dogs erupted from the bowels of the fallen campeater.<br>
In the council that followed, everyone was reminded that many times the things most harmful to us are disguised as beautiful.. necessary things...Everyone was reminded that each time Eyah falls, one of his sons comes into the world.<br>
All were cautioned to be careful of that which they pick up and bring into their nation... their homes.<br><br>
This story brings thoughts of Viet Nam to me.<br>
Did I pick up Eyah when I went to war?  Did Doc Spatz pick up Eyah when he cose to protest?  Perhaps we both did!  Foolish men do foolish things... honorable men stand up to atone for their own foolish acts and those of others...<br>
I will think on these things.<br><br>
To My Brothers with Brave Hearts.<br><br>
Tatekohomni Wambli
